            "@type": "dctypes:Text",
            "format": "text/html",
            "chars": "<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>LD.XVII.R7</em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Such a long, long, Day. [...]</strong></p>\n<p><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-d771979e-7fff-f80e-549b-da7af1bba324\">&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This phrase, imputed to Fanny, encapsulates the nature of the couple&rsquo;s &ldquo;domesticity.&rdquo; The phrase &ldquo;Oh, you do look so big!&rdquo; does appear, as do the phrases &ldquo;Dear me, dear me, there never was such a long day as this!&rdquo; and &ldquo;Good gracious, Edmund&rdquo; (LD 674). Given the presence of the future-oriented direction in the next note, it is possible that Dickens was testing out phrases for Fanny here.&nbsp;</p>"
        }
